<paragraph id="B84D36D59900FFFDFF5B463F1D0BF954" blockId="17.[164,780,1060,1786]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="8A86EAC79900FFFDFF5B463F1E5CFB97" box="[164,292,1061,1082]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">Discussion:</emphasis>
No other specimen referable to this species was cited after the description, and the only other 
<taxonomicName id="7FF24D569900FFFDFF11467B1E16FBDB" box="[238,366,1121,1142]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pachycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8A86EAC79900FFFDFF11467B1E16FBDB" box="[238,366,1121,1142]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">Pachycerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined from the Arabian Peninsula belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="7FF24D569900FFFDFE7E469B1E8EFB38" authority="Meregalli, 2009" authorityName="Meregalli" authorityYear="2009" box="[385,502,1152,1174]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pachycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hippali" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="8A86EAC79900FFFDFE7E469B1E8EFB38" box="[385,502,1152,1174]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">P. hippali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="91B557BC9900FFFDFDFB469A1D1AFB38" box="[516,610,1152,1173]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, a completely different taxon. Hence, the true identity of 
<taxonomicName id="7FF24D569900FFFDFD4C46851FA7FB7E" baseAuthorityName="Tewfik" baseAuthorityYear="1942" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pachycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="efflatouni">
<emphasis id="8A86EAC79900FFFDFD4C46851FA7FB7E" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">P. efflatouni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains uncertain. The original description is relatively good, although it particularizes nonspecific traits, which are sometimes even typical of the entire family or subfamily, and are thus devoid of any significant value in the characterization of this species. The text and the schematic drawings of the body suggest that this species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="7FF24D569900FFFDFD09476F1F89FA05" baseAuthorityName="Faust" baseAuthorityYear="1888" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pachycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="badeni">
<emphasis id="8A86EAC79900FFFDFD09476F1F89FA05" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">P. badeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. It is 12-mm long (probably including the rostrum), and is characterized by four black round spots on the elytra, two on the base and two on the declivity, behind the apex of interval 5, forming a distinctive pattern; it should have simple scales on the elytra and have bifid to multifid scales on the rostrum. Refer to 
<bibRefCitation id="DC634B249900FFFDFE2D44511D08F9CC" author="Tewfik M" box="[466,624,1611,1633]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" pagination="171 - 174" refId="ref23675" refString="Tewfik M. 1942. A new weevil from Southern Arabia: Cleonus (Pachycerus) Efflatouni nov. spec. (Coleoptera: Curculionidae-Cleoninae). Bulletin de la Societe Fouad 1 er d'Entomologie 26: 171 - 174." type="journal article" year="1942">Tewfik (1942)</bibRefCitation>
for the complete description: a detailed comparative discussion between the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="7FF24D569900FFFDFDB444931DACF930" baseAuthorityName="Tewfik" baseAuthorityYear="1942" box="[587,724,1672,1694]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pachycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="efflatouni">
<emphasis id="8A86EAC79900FFFDFDB444931DACF930" box="[587,724,1672,1694]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">P. efflatouni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the characters of 
<taxonomicName id="7FF24D569900FFFDFE8E44BD1E8FF911" authority="Meregalli, 2009" authorityName="Meregalli" authorityYear="2009" box="[369,503,1703,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pachycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahelicus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="8A86EAC79900FFFDFE8E44BD1E8FF911" box="[369,503,1703,1724]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">P. sahelicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="91B557BC9900FFFDFDFE44BD1D21F911" box="[513,601,1703,1724]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is given in the description of the latter species. The original drawings are reproduced here in 
<figureCitation id="20C92A509900FFFDFE0144FE1D0BF954" box="[510,627,1764,1786]" captionStart="Figure 70" captionStartId="18.[144,223,1276,1295]" captionTargetBox="[155,1422,195,1241]" captionTargetId="figure-244@18.[144,1425,195,1246]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 70. Pachycerus efflatouni (Tewfik, 1942). Reproduction of the original drawings (from Tewfik, 1942: 173; ‘Fig. 1: Dorsal view. – Fig. 2: Lateral view. – Fig. 3: The antenna. – Fig. 4: Middle left leg. – Fig. 5: Last tarsal segment of middle left leg, ventral aspect. – Fig. 6: Quinquefid scale-like hair. – Fig. 7: Bifid scale-like hair. – Fig. 8: Fid-like scaly hair’)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443543/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">Figure 70.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
